rComments: I'm personally not a fan of English but I enjoyed having Keith. He is a tough marker and has high expectations when it comes to papers. I think it's because he's pretty clear with the criteria he's looking for. He's really into participation so speak up if you know the answer to his question. Textbook not necessary.

Communicates well and is clear in his in-class lessons. Can be a little long-winded at times but is very approachable and always willing to help his students. He is a great educator! Wish there were more like him.
It feels like the professor drags out his sentences just to fill up class time. We could have finished 2 hours early if didn't. Good sense of humour, tedious work
Kin of boring, don't know if it was him or the class he was teaching. Otherwise not too strict on people who hand essays in late - like 2% per day. Pretty chill.

He was a decent professor, explained concepts in a straightforward manner. His marking was also fair, if you put the effort in you got the mark to show for it. Not hard to approach either, a very nice guy. He probably could have cut the class time in half, though.

Honestly, he is a very nice person but doesnt know how to teach at all. Classes are SOOO dry. His 3 hour lectures could be summed up in about 25 minutes. Keeps saying " we will talk about this at another lecture" .. and never actually gets around to explaining anything thoroughly. Unprepared and drags the class out! Excellent TA on the other hand!

It was his first class, ever, and he was so eager to do well. He nailed it ps. He was funny in class, and covered the material in a way that involved the whole class every lecture. There was a ridiculously easy grammar quiz every week, 3 simple essays and the final exam was such a joke. Take his class, you will love it.
